i## Merging RUN Commands		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iUpon opening the Dockerfile, I immediately spotted a basic mistake:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  FROM debian:stretch		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  MAINTAINER Lan Tian "lantian@lantian.pub"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ENV NGINX_VERSION=1.15.1 OPENSSL_VERSION=OpenSSL_1_1_1-pre8		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  RUN apt-get update -q \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && apt-get -y upgrade \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && apt-get -y install build-essential git autoconf automake libtool wget tar zlib1g-dev libpcre3 libpcre3-dev unzip libjemalloc-dev patch		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  RUN cd /tmp \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && wget -q http://nginx.org/download/nginx-${NGINX_VERSION}.tar.gz \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && tar xf nginx-${NGINX_VERSION}.tar.gz \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && # Compilation process follows		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDuring image builds, Docker creates a "layer" for each instruction,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istacking them to form the final image.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe first RUN command creates a layer containing nginx dependencies		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand temporary apt-get files. The subsequent compilation in the second		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iRUN operates on a new layer above the dependency layer, leaving the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioriginal dependency files untouched. Even if I later run `apt-get		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iclean` , it only marks files for deletion in the top layer — the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifiles persist in the dependency layer.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe solution is to chain both RUN commands using `&&` and backslashes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito combine them into a single layer. I initially separated these		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icommands during testing to reuse downloaded dependencies while		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idebugging compilation issues, but forgot to revert this after testing!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter merging, the image size immediately decreased by 25 MB. Though		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i175 MB was an improvement, it remained excessive.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Using Alpine as the Base Image		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI previously used Debian due to familiarity and tools like apt-get,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibut its ~125 MB base image is bulky. Alpine Linux — a ~5 MB distro		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwidely adopted in Docker — became my choice for size reduction.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, I replaced `FROM debian:stretch` with `FROM alpine` (using the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilatest version; specify if version-sensitive).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNext, I mapped Debian dependencies to Alpine equivalents using apk:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOriginal Debian dependencies:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  apt-get update -q		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  apt-get -y install build-essential git autoconf automake libtool wget tar zlib1g-dev libpcre3 libpcre3-dev unzip libjemalloc-dev patch		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAlpine equivalent:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  apk --no-cache add build-base git autoconf automake libtool wget tar zlib-dev pcre-dev unzip jemalloc-dev patch linux-headers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe `--no-cache` flag fetches packages directly from repositories (like `apt-get		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iupdate` ) and auto-clears caches (like `apt-get clean` ).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSimilarly, I adjusted dependency removal. Original Debian cleanup:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  apt-get purge -y unzip -q git autoconf libtool automake build-essential		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  apt-get autoremove -y --purge		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAlpine cleanup:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  apk del build-base git autoconf automake wget tar unzip patch linux-headers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis reduced the image to 17 MB! Local `docker images` shows 39.6 MB		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iincluding Alpine — dramatically smaller. The savings come not just		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom Alpine's size but also its lightweight musl C library.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
